{"name":"Kabir's Philosophy","id":114,"content":"<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kabir\" target=\"_blank\">Kabir</a>&nbsp;was a mystic poet who spent his life as a normal household and yet deeply involved in spirituality. He loved music, he loved love itself, he criticized the institutional expressions of God in form of religion, he criticized the vain pursuit of supernatural by renouncing the world. His religion was not defined, after his death his disciples even disputed over whether his body should be disposed as per Hindu&nbsp;or Muslim tradition.</p>\n\n<p>His poems express his thoughts precisely.</p>\n\n<p>Here&#39;s a list of his poems:-</p>\n\n<hr />\n<blockquote>\n<p><em>mo ko kah&acirc;n dh&ucirc;nro bande</em>.</p>\n\n<p>...</p>\n\n<p><em>kahat kabīr suno bhaī sādho maiṅ to hūṅ vishvās meṅ</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>Complete song: <a href=\"https://wahiduddin.net/dance/dance_docs/Moko.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>. Kabir negates all traditional spiritual practices and artefacts. Kabir says that (God) whom you seek in various activities is right then when you seek Him. He is in faith.</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://kavitakosh.org/kk/%E0%A4%AE%E0%A5%8B%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%8B_%E0%A4%95%E0%A4%B9%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%82_%E0%A4%A2%E0%A5%82%E0%A4%81%E0%A4%A2%E0%A5%87_%E0%A4%B0%E0%A5%87_%E0%A4%AC%E0%A4%A8%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%A6%E0%A5%87_/_%E0%A4%95%E0%A4%AC%E0%A5%80%E0%A4%B0\" target=\"_blank\">Complete Hindi Poem</a>, <a href=\"https://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/sok/sok002.htm\" target=\"_blank\">Tagore&#39;s&nbsp;English Translation</a></p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p><em>pānī bich mīn piyāsī.</em></p>\n\n<p><em>...</em></p>\n\n<p><em>kahat kabīr, sunau bhāī sādho, sahaj mile avināsī ..</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>Once again, how easy it is find God.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>We can&#39;t say that Kabir was against meditation, silence, solitude etc, he was up for true meditation which is achieved after one finds His within heart:-</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p><em><a href=\"http://kavitakosh.org/kk/%E0%A4%AE%E0%A4%A8_%E0%A4%AE%E0%A4%B8%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%A4_%E0%A4%B9%E0%A5%81%E0%A4%86_%E0%A4%A4%E0%A4%AC_%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%AF%E0%A5%8B%E0%A4%82_%E0%A4%AC%E0%A5%8B%E0%A4%B2%E0%A5%88_/_%E0%A4%95%E0%A4%AC%E0%A5%80%E0%A4%B0\" target=\"_blank\">man mast huā tab kyoṅ bolai.</a></em></p>\n\n<p><em>...</em></p>\n\n<p><em>kahai &#39;kabīr suno bhaī sādho, sāhab mil gae til olai॥</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://thehappybaba.blogspot.com/2012/04/wonderful-kabir-bhajan.html\" target=\"_blank\">Meaning in English</a>.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p><em>Kasturi kundali basai, mrig dhundai van mahi<br />\nAaise ghat ghat Ram hain , duniya dekhe nahi.</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>Kabir criticzed vain search [outside] for something that is within.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>We can&#39;t say that Kabir was against saints and monks per se. He defintely praised true saints:-</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p><em><a href=\"http://kavitakosh.org/kk/%E0%A4%B8%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%A7%E0%A5%81-%E0%A4%AE%E0%A4%B9%E0%A4%BF%E0%A4%AE%E0%A4%BE_/_%E0%A4%95%E0%A4%AC%E0%A5%80%E0%A4%B0\" target=\"_blank\">kabīr soī din bhalā, jā din sādhu milāy</a> .<br />\naṅk bhare bhari bheriye, pāp sharīr jāy ..</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>We can&#39;t say that Kabir was against ascetic life per se:-</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p><em><a href=\"http://kavitakosh.org/kk/%E0%A4%86%E0%A4%9A%E0%A4%B0%E0%A4%A3_%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%80_%E0%A4%AE%E0%A4%B9%E0%A4%BF%E0%A4%AE%E0%A4%BE_/_%E0%A4%95%E0%A4%AC%E0%A5%80%E0%A4%B0\" target=\"_blank\">bolī ṭholī maskharī, haňsī khel harām .</a><br />\nmad māyā aur istarī, nahi sant ke kām ..</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p><em>संसारी से प्रीतड़ी, सरै न एको काम |<br />\nदुविधा में दोनों गये, माया मिली न राम ||</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p><em>स्वारथ का सब कोई सगा, सारा ही जग जान |<br />\nबिन स्वारथ आदर करे, सो नर चतुर सुजान ||</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Kabir also emphasized&nbsp;self-respect:-</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p><em><a href=\"http://kavitakosh.org/kk/%E0%A4%B8%E0%A4%A6%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%86%E0%A4%9A%E0%A4%B0%E0%A4%A3_%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%80_%E0%A4%AE%E0%A4%B9%E0%A4%BF%E0%A4%AE%E0%A4%BE_/_%E0%A4%95%E0%A4%AC%E0%A5%80%E0%A4%B0\" target=\"_blank\">māňgan gai so mar rahai, marai ju māňgan jāhiṅ .</a><br />\ntinate pahile ve mare, hot karat haiṅ nahiṅ ..</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>Begging is like death...</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://kavitakosh.org/kk/%E0%A4%B8%E0%A4%82%E0%A4%97%E0%A4%A4%E0%A4%BF_%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%80_%E0%A4%AE%E0%A4%B9%E0%A4%BF%E0%A4%AE%E0%A4%BE_/_%E0%A4%95%E0%A4%AC%E0%A5%80%E0%A4%B0\" target=\"_blank\">Kabir also emphasized the social circle of saints, wholesome acts and speech.</a></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://kavitakosh.org/kk/%E0%A4%B8%E0%A5%81%E0%A4%96-%E0%A4%A6%E0%A5%81%E0%A4%83%E0%A4%96_%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%80_%E0%A4%AE%E0%A4%B9%E0%A4%BF%E0%A4%AE%E0%A4%BE_/_%E0%A4%95%E0%A4%AC%E0%A5%80%E0%A4%B0\">Kabir also emphasized the devotion towards saintly Guru</a>.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<hr />\n<blockquote>\n<p><em>sādho, dekho jag baurānā </em></p>\n\n<p><em>....</em></p>\n\n<p><em>yā vidhi haňsat chalat hai, hamako āp kahāvai syānā .<br />\nkahai kabīr suno bhāī sādho, inameṅ kaun divānā&nbsp;</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>Kabir criticizes the hypocrisy of so-called scholors of religions Hindu, Muslim included, who despite having read books don&#39;t know themselves, who practice many rituals but don&#39;t have compassion.&nbsp;Kabir says to himself, <em>&quot;None of them is true lover [of God]&quot;</em></p>\n\n<hr />\n<blockquote>\n<p><em>rahanā nahiṅ des birānā hai.</em></p>\n\n<p><em>...</em></p>\n\n<p><em>kahat &#39;kabīr suno bhāī sādho, satugaru nām ṭhikānā hai॥</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>As all wise people Kabir also realised the nature of this world which is based on&nbsp;impermanence and delusionary games.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p>Kabir also realised the impermanent&nbsp;nature of existence, the mortality of humans&nbsp;and advised against ego.</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p><em><a href=\"http://kavitakosh.org/kk/%E0%A4%B5%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%AF%E0%A4%B5%E0%A4%B9%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%B0_%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%80_%E0%A4%AE%E0%A4%B9%E0%A4%BF%E0%A4%AE%E0%A4%BE_/_%E0%A4%95%E0%A4%AC%E0%A5%80%E0%A4%B0\">kabīr garb n kījiye, is jīvan kī ās .</a><br />\nṭesū fūlā divas das, khaṅkhar bhayā palās ..</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>He also criticized the vain things that people spend their lives in without knowing that this human life is a gift to realise something that is not possible for other animals.</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p><em>rāt gaňvāī soyekar, divas gaňvāye khāye .<br />\nhīrā janam amol thā, kauḍī badale jāy ..</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>If human life is not used to realise&nbsp;something special, your and your children&#39;s life is just like that of insects: they come and go.</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p><em><a href=\"http://kavitakosh.org/kk/%E0%A4%95%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%B2_%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%80_%E0%A4%AE%E0%A4%B9%E0%A4%BF%E0%A4%AE%E0%A4%BE_/_%E0%A4%95%E0%A4%AC%E0%A5%80%E0%A4%B0\" target=\"_blank\">beṭā jāye kyā huā, kahā bajāve thāl .</a><br />\nāvan jāvan hoy rahā, jyoṅ kīḍī kā nāl ..</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<hr />\n<p>Kabir emphasized on wholesome speech. The speech that saints utter, without ego, without any sort of violence, no crookedness, no hypocrisy; their speech is like clean water which gives comfort and calmness&nbsp;to others. Only saintly person can bear harsh words. The importance of words can be seen by observing our behaviour towards Crows and Cuckoos, crows don&#39;t take your wealth yet they are hated by everyone, Cuckoos don&#39;t give anything yet they are loved, just. by the virtue of sweet words(sound).</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p><em><a href=\"http://kavitakosh.org/kk/%E0%A4%B6%E0%A4%AC%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%A6_%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%80_%E0%A4%AE%E0%A4%B9%E0%A4%BF%E0%A4%AE%E0%A4%BE_/_%E0%A4%95%E0%A4%AC%E0%A5%80%E0%A4%B0\" target=\"_blank\">कुटिल वचन सबते बुरा, जारि करे सब छार |</a><br />\nसाधु वचन जल रूप है, बरसै अमृत धार ||</em></p>\n\n<p><em>खोद खाद धरती सहै, काट कूट बनराय |कुटिल वचन साधु सहै, और से सहा न जाय ||</em></p>\n\n<p><em>मुख आवै सोई कहै, बोलै नहीं विचार |<br />\nहते पराई आत्मा, जीभ बाँधि तरवार ||</em></p>\n\n<p><em>शब्द जु ऐसा बोलिये, मन का आपा खोय |<br />\nऔरन को शीतल करे, आपन को सुख होय ||</em></p>\n\n<p><em>कागा काको धन हरै, कोयल काको देत |<br />\nमीठा शब्द सुनाय को, जग अपनो करि लेत ||</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<hr />\n<p>Kabir also emphasized how important the determination is, especially for saints, knights/warriors/bravehearts, and for <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sati_(practice)\" target=\"_blank\">Sati</a> women. They leave for their journey by leaving any hope/attachment for mortal body. If their&nbsp;determination shakes, they are not only mocked they also lose the charm/shine/ight on their face.</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p><em><a href=\"http://kavitakosh.org/kk/%E0%A4%B8%E0%A4%A4%E0%A4%BF_%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%80_%E0%A4%AE%E0%A4%B9%E0%A4%BF%E0%A4%AE%E0%A4%BE_/_%E0%A4%95%E0%A4%AC%E0%A5%80%E0%A4%B0\" target=\"_blank\">ये तीनों उलटे बुरे, साधु, सती और सूर |</a><br />\nजग में हँसी होयगी, मुख पर रहै न नूर ||</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<hr />\n<p>Kabir on spiritual psychology:</p>\n\n<p>Kabit emphasized that we need to control our minds. And mind can be taken under control by gaining knowledge and wisdom.</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p><em><a href=\"http://kavitakosh.org/kk/%E0%A4%AE%E0%A4%A8_%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%80_%E0%A4%AE%E0%A4%B9%E0%A4%BF%E0%A4%AE%E0%A4%BE_/_%E0%A4%95%E0%A4%AC%E0%A5%80%E0%A4%B0\" target=\"_blank\">मन के मते न चलिये, मन के मते अनेक |</a><br />\nजो मन पर असवार है, सो साधु कोई एक ||</em></p>\n\n<p><em>मनुवा तो पंछी भया, उड़ि के चला अकास |<br />\nऊपर ही ते गिरि पड़ा, मन माया के पास ||</em></p>\n\n<p><em>मन पंछी तब लग उड़ै, विषय वासना माहिं |<br />\nज्ञान बाज के झपट में, तब लगि आवै नाहिं ||</em></p>\n\n<p><em>महमंता मन मारि ले, घट ही माहीं घेर |<br />\nजबही चालै पीठ दे, आँकुस दै दै फेर ||</em></p>\n\n<p><em>मैं जानूँ मन मरि गया, मरि के हुआ भूत |<br />\nमूये पीछे उठि लगा, ऐसा मेरा पूत ||</em></p>\n\n<p><em>मन को मिरतक देखि के, मति माने विश्वास |<br />\nसाधु तहाँ लौं भय करे, जौ लौं पिंजर साँस ||</em></p>\n\n<p><em>कबीर मिरतक देखकर, मति धरो विश्वास |<br />\nकबहुँ जागै भूत है करे पिड़का नाश ||</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>Mind&#39;s attachment is highly linked with physical body&#39;s attachment.</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p><em><a href=\"http://kavitakosh.org/kk/%E0%A4%9C%E0%A5%80%E0%A4%B5%E0%A4%A8_%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%80_%E0%A4%AE%E0%A4%B9%E0%A4%BF%E0%A4%AE%E0%A4%BE_/_%E0%A4%95%E0%A4%AC%E0%A5%80%E0%A4%B0\" target=\"_blank\">जब लग आश शरीर की, मिरतक हुआ न जाय |</a><br />\nकाया माया मन तजै, चौड़े रहा बजाय ||</em></p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<hr />\n<p>On Life and Death</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p><em>जीवन में मरना भला, जो मरि जानै कोय |<br />\nमरना पहिले जो मरै, अजय अमर सो होय ||</em></p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","authorId":null,"subject":"philosophy","tags":null,"img":null,"summary":null,"lastUpdated":"2020-05-14T11:34:45.018+0000"}